</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. TALKS STOPPED, SOUTH YEMEN SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kuwaiti-mediated talks between the United States and South Yemen about a 
resumption of diplomatic ties have stopped, South Yemen's foreign minister was 
quoted Sunday as saying. 
</P>
<P>
Abdulaziz Dali told the United Arab Emirates newspaper Al Ittihad that his 
country is not against normalized relations but will not accept any imposed 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
He would not specify any conditions but added, "We reject talk that South Yemen 
supports terrorism." 
</P>
<P>
South Yemen last November signed a pact to merge with Yemen and has announced 
sweeping reforms of its Marxist political system. It broke ties with Washington 
one year after gaining independence from Britain in 1968. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021990-0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 178543 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 19, 1990, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
