NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
FLORIDA; 
</P>
<P>
SOVIET LAWMAKERS TOUR SHUTTLE SITE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soviet defense committee lawmakers toured the Kennedy Space Center in Florida a 
few hours before the countdown began for the Thursday liftoff of the space 
shuttle Atlantis, carrying a secret satellite that reportedly will spy on the 
Soviet Union. When asked what he thought of the spy satellite, Vladimir 
Lapygin, the committee chairman and head of the delegation, replied with a 
smile: "We have no special secrets . . . . I think you are wasting your money." 
The group toured areas where shuttles are worked on, a launching control center 
and a launch pad. 
</P>
